PSD buildings will remain closed for the remainder of the week due to extremely poor air quality. The current and forecasted air quality from surrounding fires is impacting our ability to resume ventilation in school buildings. As a result, HVAC systems will remain off through Friday, Sept. 18.

Free meal distribution is canceled the week of Sept. 14 and will resume Monday, Sept. 21

Right at School Distance Learning Camp is canceled the week of Sept. 14

There is no change to the Continuous (Distance) Learning student schedule for the week of Sept. 14.

Share in the comments below, or email your pictures to our newest email address: dessieevansphotos@gmail.com.*

And don't forget - you can come by the school tonight between 4-7 to take a back to school photo with our growth ruler!

We can't wait to see what our students are up to!

Dessie F. Evans Elementary

Then & Now: Toaster

Today, toasters come in all sizes and price ranges. What kind of toaster do you have?

#KarshnerCenter#KarshnerCenterProud

post_text: Since March, a ‚Äònew normal‚Äô of teaching and learning has evolved. Widespread access to devices and integrated technologies for students, families, and staff have positioned the District well for large-scale remote learning. An example of this is Family University, a collection of 50 short videos for parents. This learning resource for families and students provides training on District technology tools and platforms to support learning at home. https://bit.ly/3g5Eaq5

Families were offered free face masks during the Monday Meal Pickup Program at five Puyallup elementary schools on July 20. Staff from Communities In Schools of Puyallup handed the masks out as families drove by to pick up 5-Day Meal Packs.

The City of Puyallup - Government Emergency Operations Center received the 1,500 masks from the Pierce County Department of Emergency Management and worked with the District to arrange the distribution.

The meal program takes place on Mondays at Firgrove, Stewart, Sunrise, Wildwood, and Waller Road through August 28.

Stewart Elementary
June 20 at 4:46 AM ¬∑

Today was a bittersweet day. It definitely did not feel like the last day of school, but we're used to things not feeling "normal" when it comes to anything related to school since March 13th!

A bright spot for today was the Stewart Stars Drive By. Our staff loved seeing those of you who could drive by and honk, wave, and cheer. Seeing your faces made our hearts feel whole again. We hoped you enjoyed it as much as we did!

Thank you for giving this principal so much to be thankful for. I LOVE our Stewart family and will forever be grateful for the love, kindness, and compassion you have shared with me.

Once a Star, always a Star. I will see you again in the fall and promise not to be a stranger. Stewart Stars Shine Bright! How often? EVERY DAY! Shine on and shine bright!

This week, take some time for gratitude. If you think you don‚Äôt have time because of all you need to do, consider the research. People who practice gratitude have an improved attitude, have improved physical and psychological health, feel more positive, are able to handle challenges more effectively, and are more likely to have lifelong happiness. When you face life‚Äôs challenges with gratitude, they become less overwhelming and more manageable, creating a sense of well-being.‚†Ä
‚†Ä
If you still aren‚Äôt sure, give it a try this week and see for yourself. Try one of these ideas: ‚†Ä
‚†Ä
- Go outside for a Gratitude Scavenger Hunt, ‚†Ä
- Write a list each day of things you are thankful for,‚†Ä
- Call or send a note to someone you appreciate,‚†Ä
- Be creative and show gratitude through art, dance or music,‚†Ä
- Come up with your own idea!‚†Ä
‚†Ä
Even taking one minute to be mindfully grateful each day, especially first thing in the morning, can have a positive impact on your well-being and state of mind! Read more: ‚†Ä
https://bit.ly/3eyHoTc

post_text:
If you describe a person you know or have learned about who overcame an obstacle or challenge in his or her life, you would be describing someone resilient.

Resilience is the ability to keep trying, even when things are hard. We are not born with resilience; it is something that we learn through each difficult event we encounter. It is a skill that we use throughout our lives at school, in our jobs, in our relationships. Sometimes we challenge ourselves by learning a new hobby like playing the piano or learning to longboard. Sometimes the challenges comes to us, like a school closure and stay-at-home order. Either way, we can use these challenges to learn how to overcome difficult events. Watch this video to learn ways to become more resilient!

Becoming Resilient for Kids: https://bit.ly/2A4E2rm

Parents, here is an article with more information: https://bit.ly/2zrnFVK

Read more Social Emotional Learning passages on our website: https://bit.ly/2zrnFVK

Whether you‚Äôre a student or an adult, we all have a lot on our minds right now, and those thoughts can turn into worries like:

1. The worst thing I can imagine is going to happen.
2. I won‚Äôt be able to handle whatever it is that happens.
3. This situation and these feelings are going to continue forever.

When worries continuously play in our head, our brain becomes anxious, and our body becomes stressed. The good news is that we CAN do something to change our mindset and reduce our anxiety. https://copingskillsforkids.com/calming-anxiety

For older students and adults, watch this video for inspiration to learn ‚Äúhow we can transform our anxiety into hope, joy, and compassion.‚Äù https://vimeo.com/415271348

She has been working with companies, authors, and publishers and already have collected a TON of books.
But, we want YOUR help! Next week, we will be at Abbey Carpet‚Äôs warehouse (aka the Book Barn) accepting drive by donations. The books will then quarantine in the barn before we sort and distribute them to ensure our communities safety.

post_text:
Whether you are a student or an adult, we are all experiencing stress in some way as we deal with the COVID-19 pandemic. Deep breathing is one of the best ways to lower stress in your body and is a strategy that you can use anywhere at any time. Although everyone‚Äôs reactions are different, some signs that your body could be feeling stress are faster breathing, tense muscles, upset stomach, irritability, low energy, or insomnia. Intentionally breathing deeply sends a message to your brain to calm down and relax.

Try one of these techniques the next time you feel stress in your body (or if you want to prevent stress from building up):

4-7-8 Breathing Exercise: https://bit.ly/2YWVEzN

A Japanese Method to Relax in 5 Minutes: https://bit.ly/2zpA8ZY

Lazy 8 Breathing: https://bit.ly/3bkdejL

The wagon in the Pioneer Room at Karshner Center has been a part of the museum since the early 1980‚Äôs. The wagon is half the size of a traditional wagon. It is one of the most popular sitting, playing and hands-on activity center in the museum. Preschoolers on field trips have their pictures taken in the wagon, kindergarteners pack the wagon for travel across America on the Oregon Trail during their field trip, ‚Äústory time‚Äù happens in the wagon and lots of dres-up and role playing of pioneers, general store merchants, fur traders wagon guides, school teachers and students all happen in the Pioneer room.

post_text:
People need connection! Did you know that being connected to others helps you live longer? Enables you to ward off disease? Reduces the likelihood of feeling depressed? Makes us nicer to be around? We need connections to other people every day, and that is even more true during a time of crisis like we are experiencing now.

With the stay-at-home order and so many requirements to do work and school using digital resources, take some time for person-to-person connections while maintaining a safe social distance from others. https://bit.ly/2Szgy4b

The Puyallup School Board approved a proclamation at its April 20 board meeting proclaiming April 20-24 as Public School Volunteer Week.

More than 8,000 parents, community members, and students served as Puyallup School District volunteers during this school year. They inspired success in students while nurturing and challenging them to extend beyond their reach and provide a valuable partnership link with the community.

Thank you to each of our volunteers for your dedication and hard work! https://bit.ly/3bthjTK

shared_text:
Karshner Museum and Center for Culture & Arts
April 3 at 7:13 PM ¬∑

Happy Friday! If you have visited Karshner Center you may have seen Houdini, our horned toad, visiting one of our exhibits. Well, Mr. Houdini has decided to take his adventures outside and explore Puyallup -- here he is leaving Karshner Center now.

Did you know that Dr. Warner Karshner who founded the Paul Karshner Memorial Museum in 1931 was the first person in Puyallup to drive a car and he would take people in rides up and down Meridian.

Where do you think Houdini will go next?

shared_text:
Pierce County Sheriff's Department
April 1 at 3:00 PM ¬∑

It‚Äôs April Fools Day, it‚Äôs raining outside, and you are stuck in the house with nothing to do‚Ä¶ it seems like a perfect day for the Dr. Seuss classic ‚ÄúThe Cat in the Hat‚Äù.

The book is being read and expertly voiced by Sergeant Rich Scaniffe, who has served with our department for 19 years in patrol and is a member of our SWAT Team. He currently supervises our Mountain Detachment during our swing and graveyards shifts ‚Äì so if you live anywhere between Eatonville, Roy, Graham, Kapowsin or McKenna all the way to Mount Rainier, he is helping to keep you safe at night.

Sergeant Scaniffe became a deputy because he wanted to make a difference in the community where he lives, and his favorite part of being a police officer is that you are always meeting new people and learning new things.

Thanks so much for joining us for another ‚ÄúStorytime with a Sheriff‚Äù. We hope this brings you a little fun and a lots of smiles to start your day!

**ART CONTEST**

Puyallup Parks & Recreation invites all kids ages 13 and under to enter our weekly art contest! Each Monday we will post a different theme and all entries must be original artwork posted to our Facebook page to be considered. Reply to our post with a picture of your art including first name and age by 12pm that following Friday. Please limit one entry per child. You can use any type of art you want including drawing, painting, sidewalk chalk, Play-Doh, etc. Be creative! Winner will be recognized on our Facebook page by 5pm Friday!

3/30-4/3 theme: #stayhomestayhealthy

New theme announced every Monday on our Facebook page.

We will be sharing your entries with the Puyallup Activity Center and senior living facilities to help bring them some fun during this difficult time!

Pierce County Sheriff's Department
March 28 at 3:00 PM ¬∑

Welcome back for another ‚ÄúStorytime with a Sheriff‚Äù ‚Äì who is ready to start the weekend with a walk on the wild side?

Today‚Äôs guest reader is probably the most well known police officer in Pierce County, it is our longtime spokesperson Detective Ed Troyer. Detective Troyer has been with our department since 1985 and started his career on patrol working in our west districts from Spanaway to Lakewood and the Key Peninsula. After stints in our narcotics unit and on a federal gang task force, he took the reigns in our media office.

What most people don‚Äôt know about Detective Troyer is that he spends almost all of his free time volunteering for children‚Äôs charities including Toys for Tots, Charlie‚Äôs Dinosaur, Special Olympics, and the Foster Parents Association.

Detective Troyer grew up as a wild child in Tacoma, so it was perfect fit that he chose to share with all of you ‚ÄúWhere the Wild Things Are‚Äù written and illustrated by Maurice Sendak. Enjoy!

post_text:
We found it necessary to take today and tomorrow to retool our plans for childcare and food service. As our meal services increased, our social distancing in our kitchen prep areas had to be redesigned. We are also creating call lists to be able to backfill staff for vacancies as necessary to allow us to be able to continue service and we are creating contingency plans in the event of a shelter in place order.

As of Monday March 23rd, we will be providing Monday through Friday meal service for all children 0-18 from 11:00 to 12:00 at each of our 22 elementary schools. We are also launching childcare service for medical workers and first responders Monday through Friday from 8:00-4:00 at all elementary schools beginning March 23rd. Take the survey: PSD Childcare for Healthcare Workers and First Responders

As I‚Äôm sure you can imagine, we are dealing with an unprecedented health crisis. We will continue to monitor our plans closely and will continue to adjust as needed to support the community.

Visit our website for school locations and more information. https://bit.ly/39hqTYL

3607 122nd Ave E

Emma L. Carson Elementary
March 2 at 5:15 AM ¬∑

Tomorrow we kick-off Read Across America Week. We wanted to share with you the Top 10 Benefits of reading:
1. Kids who read often and widely get better at it
2. Reading exercises our brains
3. Reading improves concentration
4. Reading teaches children about the world around them
5. Reading improves a child‚Äôs vocabulary and leads to more highly-developed language skills
6. Reading develops a child‚Äôs imagination
7. Reading helps kids develop empathy
8. Children who read do better at school
9. Reading is a great form of entertainment
10. Reading relaxes the body and calms the mind

Make a commitment to set aside at least 15 minutes per day to read a book.

"Our Carson Student Council Leaders split into three committees: Kindness Committee, March Gladness Committee and Yearbook Committee. So many great things happening in each committee. Yearbook Committee is working together to make sure that each student is well represented in our yearbook. Kindness Committee is working on a project that will soon be displayed in our Carson hallways‚Ä¶ stay tuned. March Gladness is working on the logistics of Carson‚Äôs March Gladness Project and creating posters that will be displayed in our hallways to encourage students to participate in this project that will give back to our community. These leaders are such a great representation of the hundreds of leaders that we have at Carson!"-Mrs Treich and Ms Salloum, Student Council Teachers

Huge thanks to Central Pierce Fire & Rescue Arson Dog Hansel and his handler Fire Marshal Chris Lorenz for meeting this morning with transportation and district personnel to talk about his training on surplus buses. We are honored to be able to assist Hansel as he expands his ability to sniff out accelerants in a variety of settings.

On the morning of Wed Feb 19, Hansel and Chris will visit students and staff of Stewart Elementary for additional experience. Keep watch on this page for photos!

In the new class "Intro to Culinary Science" at Aylen Junior High School, the main component is learning about food safety and focusing on Farm to Table.
The students final was an "Food Innovation" lab where students had to create a different tasting cupcake using a white flavor cake box - CUPCAKE WAR. Super proud of these students! For some this was their first recital in the program!! Great Job team! AND Parents also showed off their talents! NICE!

‚ÄúI had zero idea of what I was doing.. I honestly had no idea where to start. All I knew was I had something I craved to say.. I wanted to create art that lived on longer than I do. Perseverance and teaching yourself, every day through stress and hard work proves stuff really does progress without you realizing. One minute you're an amateur, knowing nothing, not even the basics. The next you can put pen to paper, write a song, and create art in such little time! It's crazy beautiful.‚Äù
‚Äï Scott McGoldrick

shared_text:
Communities In Schools of Puyallup
January 17 at 4:23 PM ¬∑

Struggling students and their families have a hard time accessing and navigating the maze of public and private services. There may be ample resources in a community, but rarely is there someone on the ground who is able to connect these resources with the schools and students that need them most. Through a school-based coordinator, we bring these local resources into the school where they are accessible, coordinated and accountable. At Communities In Schools, we work with everyone to change the picture of education for the students we serve. We do this by: 1. Keeping kids in school. 2. Doing whatever it takes to eliminate barriers. 3. Never giving up, on anyone.
This is accomplished through this model of Site Coordination. While services and supports might vary from school to school depending on the needs, all Site Coordinators use this proven model of Site Coordination to bring community resources into the schools to support students. #2020 #WhatWeAreMadeOf

shared_text:
Communities In Schools of Puyallup
January 3 at 4:45 PM ¬∑

With the start of a new year, and with a lot of new followers, we thought we would take some time this month to show you what Communities In Schools of Puyallup is made of. Keep an eye out every Friday for a post that will highlight where we have come from, and what makes our organization what it is!
For starters, did you know that we are a part of a national organization? There are CIS affiliates in 25 states and the District of Columbia serving 2,300 schools. Our national office provides leadership and oversight from Washington DC. Each affiliate utilizes the same model of having a Site Coordinator in a school, but tailors it to meet the specific needs of where they are located! This means that the work of empowering students to see their full potential and experiencing success in school and beyond is happening across the country! #2020 #WhatWeAreMadeOf

January 11th, 2020 at 830am ‚Äì 11:30am

The Aspiring Medical Professionals Summit will be delivered in collaboration with community medical professionals and colleges. We are hoping you will join us in that collaboration to make this an amazing experience for our Puyallup School District high school students.

The purpose of the summit is to provide students with the resources and knowledge they need in navigating a medical profession pathway they may be interested in.

There will be a keynote speaker, a medical panel, as well as an informational fair where medical professionals/colleges will give all students the time to gain more information regarding job shadow programs, technical training opportunities and receive one to one information on best pathways in the medical field.

REGISTER TO ATTEND HERE:
https://bit.ly/2LSERGH

We look forward to seeing you on the 11th.

Emerald Ridge HOSA

post_text: TONIGHT!!
shared_text:
Karshner Museum and Center for Culture & Arts
November 20, 2019 at 11:00 PM ¬∑

Conservationist and artist Becci Crowe, working to help save threatened and endangered species, has an amazing story to tell. Traveling across six continents, including 16 trips to the African Continent and over 47 countries, Becci began networking with conservation experts from around the world and participating in fieldwork. Becci's desire to study her subjects in their natural world has led to adventurous travel to remote parts of the planet where she soon discovered the challenges faced by wildlife and people sharing their environment. Becci has been to Jane‚Äôs Chimpanzee Sanctuary in Africa to work alongside Jane Goodall and now serves on the Jane Goodall Institute Board of Directors.

Join Becci Crowe at the Karshner Museum, Thursday night November 21, 2019 to hear about her travels, see wildlife photos and video as she talks about her work with conservation organizations around the world. See her beautiful artwork of the animals she has studied and helped. 6:30-8:00 pm and free admittance.

Traveling across six continents, including 16 trips to the African Continent and over 47 countries, Becci began networking with conservation experts from around the world and participating in fieldwork. Becci's desire to study her subjects in their natural world has led to adventurous travel to remote parts of the planet where she soon discovered the challenges faced by wildlife and people sharing their environment. Becci has been to Jane‚Äôs Chimpanzee Sanctuary in Africa to work alongside Jane Goodall and now serves on the Jane Goodall Institute Board of Directors.

Join Becci Crowe at the Karshner Museum, Thursday night November 21, 2019 to hear about her travels, see wildlife photos and video as she talks about her work with conservation organizations around the world. See her beautiful artwork of the animals she has studied and helped. 6:30-8:00 pm and free admittance.

Do you know what a Pangolin is? What is unusual about this animal? While it looks scaly and almost lizardy it is a mammal. Its plates (scales) are made of what our hair and fingernails are made of. It is one of the most endangered species in the world.
Join Becci Crowe as she talks about this cuddly endangered animal and what is being done to save their species. She will show photos, artwork and a video presentation talking about her adventures with wild animals and the organizations that are working to save threatened and endangered species.

Their renowned Orphans‚Äô Project allows them to respond to and rescue orphaned baby elephants, rhinos and other wild species across Kenya, so that they might enjoy a life back in the wild when grown. 247 Elephant orphans have been successfully rescued, raised and are living back in the wild by the Sheldrick Wildlife Trust. Security Guard Greg Royal served in the US Air Force for little over 20 years from November 1980 until January 2001. He spent 16 of 20 years overseas in Italy , Korea, Japan, Hawaii, Bosnia, Germany, Guam and the Philippines.

His entire time he worked in law enforcement/security and protected personnel-military and civilian, Nuclear weapons, Air Force One, and everything associated with Presidential travel.

He also worked within Security Forces unit as a criminal investigator, Information Security Manager, Logistics NCOIC, NCOIC Armory, gate Sentry and Patrolman.

He retired at the rank of Master Sergeant.

Thank you for your service!

It was a beautiful sunny morning on October 9 as many Karshner Elementary students, parents, and staff gathered at Sam Peach Park in Puyallup for Walk to School Day.

Students were welcomed by Puyallup School District Superintendent Tim Yeomans and Director of Facilities Planning Brian Devereux, Puyallup Interim City Manager Steve Kirkelie, and City Councilman Jim Kastama.

They were celebrating pedestrian safety and the installation of new Rectangular Rapid Flashing Beacons (RRFB) at the existing crosswalk across 15th St NW (at 8th Ave NW), located near the northwest corner of Karshner Elementary.

Puyallup Career & Technical Education is at Kalles Junior High.
October 10, 2019 at 7:07 PM ¬∑ Puyallup, WA ¬∑

High honors were earned by several current and former Kalles Junior High students! Under the leadership of teacher, Heidi Matson, ten students were recognized for their efforts in their Microsoft Office course. These outstanding students earned four or more industry recognized certificates. Puyallup School District partner, CCI Learning, awarded scholarships to students across the state who ranked in the top ten of all certificate earners. Congratulations! #GoPuyallupCTE @KallesJuniorHigh

Hey Washington State teachers, did you know Legacy Washington offers lesson plans with each of our projects?! Our latest even includes printable posters of the exhibit panels!!

‚ÄúAhead of the Curve: Washington Women Lead the Way‚Äù lesson plan and posters are available online: www.sos.wa.gov/legacy/ahead-of-the-curve/lesson-plan.aspx

The lesson plans follow the inquiry arc as outlined in the College, Career, Civic Life (C3) Framework for Social Studies State Standards and are common core aligned (Washington State standards) to challenge students in essential reading, writing, speaking and listening skills.

shared_text:
Emerald Ridge High School
October 9, 2019 at 4:49 PM ¬∑

Emerald Ridge would like to invite you to Vaping: A Conversation About the Negative Health Effects of Using. This event will take place next Tuesday, October 15th from 5:30-7 p.m. in the ERHS Auditorium. The conversation includes personnel from the medical community, the Pierce County Fire Department, Law Enforcement, Health and Safety, and Prevention and Intervention. There will be a question and answer period and light refreshments will be served.

Throwback Thursday!

Central School: Built in 1886 with additions in 1890. In 1903 another four-room addition was added. The school burned down in 1922. Central School was located at the current site of Karshner Center.

post_text: So #PSDProud of our Karshner Museum and Center for Culture & Arts!
shared_text:
KCTS 9
September 30, 2019 at 11:55 PM ¬∑

Since 1931, this free admission museum has charmed visitors with an eclectic mix of more than 7,000 artifacts, from Coast Salish baskets to a sizable collection of geological objects and insects on display. http://bit.ly/2mmCG4K

Congratulations to the Karshner Museum and Center for Culture & Arts on being recognized as one of the seven recipients of the 2019 Golden Apple Moments for their outstanding achievements in education in Washington State. For more Golden Apple Moments, presented by KCTS 9 and PEMCO Insurance, visit: https://kcts9.org/programs/golden-apple-moments.
